{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17227"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17227"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0,0.96,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69648"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55101"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"10049"},{"type":"tags","id":"10052"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23329"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69648"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECholecystokinin is a peptide hormone and secreted from the I-cells in the proximal small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary physiological actions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promotes intestinal water absorption and bicarbonate secretion","Increases gastric acid secretion and motility","Increases gastric emptying and small intestinal transit","Stimulates gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion","Stimulates insulin release and glucose uptake"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary actions of \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystokinin include gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion\u003C/strong\u003E. It is released from I-cells in the duodenum and proximal jejunum in response to the presence of proteins and fats. This facilitates fat digestion by coordinating the delivery of bile and digestive enzymes into the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases gastric acid secretion and motility\u003C/strong\u003E - Cholecystokinin actually inhibits gastric acid secretion and reduces gastric motility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates insulin release and glucose uptake\u003C/strong\u003E - These are actions of incretin hormones like GLP-1, not cholecystokinin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes intestinal water absorption and bicarbonate secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - These are not primary actions of cholecystokinin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases gastric emptying and small intestinal transit\u003C/strong\u003E - Cholecystokinin slows gastric emptying as part of the ileal brake mechanism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional effects of cholecystokinin include promoting satiety and reducing food intake through actions on the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholecystokinin is secreted by duodenal I-cells in response to proteins and fats in the small intestine.","Cholecystokinin causes gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion.","Cholecystokinin also reduces gastric emptying and promotes satiety."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55101"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17227"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55101"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:48:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:48:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9917"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69648"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synony